osition for choir & baroque ensemble by Gustavo Trujillo \n|-\n|[[Concerto Italiano]], [[Rinaldo Alessandrini]]\n|2017\n|\n|[[Na\u00efve Records|Naive]]\n|period strings and continuo\n|-\n|Martin Heini\n|2017\n|St. Katharina Parish Church, [[Horw]], Switzerland\n|Guild\n|organ\n|-\n|Ji (Ji-Yong)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.warnerclassics.com/release/5536821,0190295719371/ji-bach-goldberg-variations|title=Ji // Bach Goldberg Variations|last=Erato|first=Warner Classics /|work=Warner Classics|access-date=2018-06-16|language=en-UK}}</ref>\n|2018\n|\n|Warner Classics\n|piano\n|-\n|Rainwater, Anne\n|December 14, 2018\n|[[Oakland, California]]\n|\n|piano\n|}\n\n----\n<small>Without recording date - To be inserted in the list</small>\n*[[J\u00f6rg Demus]] - mid-1950s - Westminster WL 5241 - ''piano''\n*[[Ito Ema]]<ref>Billed as the premier audiophile recording of the Variations, recorded with handmade microphones and independent circuitry for simultaneous digital and analog recordings.</ref> - MA Recordings M024A\n*[[Zuzana R\u016f\u017ei\u010dkov\u00e1]] - Erato \u2013 ERA 9034 - Neupert (Mercier-Ythier) ''harpsichord''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Compositions for Organ, Keyboard and Lute by Johann Sebastian Bach}}\n[[Category:Discographies of compositions by J. S. Bach]]\n", "name_user": "D\u00f6nerwetter1965", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldberg_Variations_discography"}
{"title_page": "In Harihar Nagar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2010}} \n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = In Harihar Nagar chapra\n| image          = In Harihar Nagar.jpg\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Siddique-Lal]]\n| producer       = Khais-Kuriachan\n| writer         = Siddique-Lal\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]]<br>[[Siddique (actor)|Siddique]]<br>[[Jagadish]]<br>[[Ashokan (actor)|Ashokan]]\n| music          = [[S. Balakrishnan (composer)|S. Balakrishnan]]\n| cinematography = [[Venu (cinematographer)|Venu]]\n| editing        = Gaurishekar K. R.\n| distributor    = Swargachitra\n| studio         = Mohsin Priya Combines\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1990}}\n| runtime        =\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Malayalam]]\n}}\n\n'''''In Harihar Nagar''''' is a 1990 Indian [[Malayalam]]-language [[Comedy film|comedy]] [[Thriller film|thriller]] film written and directed by [[Siddique-Lal]]. It stars [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]], [[Siddique (actor)|Siddique]], [[Jagadish]] and [[Ashokan (actor)|Ashokan]] as four happy-go-lucky best friends competing to woo their new neighbor girl. The film's music was composed by [[S. Balakrishnan (composer)|S. Balakrishnan]].\n\nThe film was a commercial success at the box office. It has been recognised as one of the iconic comedy films in Malayalam cinema.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2009/01/02/stories/2009010250630200.htm|title=Return to Harihar Nagar |author=Vijay George|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=2 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/malayalam/top-stories/2008/in-harihar-nagar-2-090908.html|title=In Harihar Nagar-2|date=9 September 2008|publisher=[[Oneindia.in]]|accessdate=2 January 2011}}</ref> The film has spawned two sequels\u2014''[[2 Harihar Nagar]]'' (2009) and ''[[In Ghost House Inn]]'' (2010), both directed by [[Lal (director)|Lal]]. ''In Harihar Nagar'' was remade twice in [[Hindi]] as ''[[Parda Hai Parda (1992 film)|Parda Hai Parda]]'' and ''[[Dhol (film)|Dhol]]'', in [[Kannada]] as ''[[Nagaradalli Nayakaru]]'', in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] as ''[[MGR Nagaril (1991 film)|MGR Nagaril]]'', and in [[Telugu language|Telugu]] as ''Madhuranagarilo''.\n\n==Plot==\n{{copyedit |date=April 2020}}\nMahadevan ([[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]]), Govindan Kutty ([[Siddique (actor)|Siddique]]), Appukuttan ([[Jagadish]]) and Thomas Kutty ([[Ashokan (actor)|Ashokan]]) are four young men who live in the housing colony named 'Harihar Nagar.' The movie starts with an incident that takes place in [[Mumbai|Bombay]], where a burglar, John Honai, breaks in looking for a specific briefcase. In the next scene the four young men make an appearance, using their wiles to impress young, neighborhood girls. A girl, Maya ([[Geetha Vijayan]]), along with her grandparents relocate to Harihar Nagar and happen to be Mahadevan's new neighbors. The four try to win her over on many occasions. One day they see her posting a letter and they bribe the postman to get hold of the letter. On reading the contents of the letter, they learn that Maya has come to Harihar Nagar to learn about the death of her brother - Sethu Madhavan ([[Suresh Gopi]]). \n\nMaya visits the house of Andrew's ([[Saikumar (Malayalam actor)|Saikumar]]), a friend of Sethu Madhavan. She asks Andrew's mother, called Ammachi by him and his friends, ([[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]]) to contact her if she gets any information about her brother. The four men approach Ammachi, pretending to be Sethu's friends. They manage to get Sethu's photograph by telling her that they want it for the colony's sports club. Maya gets this information from Ammachi and meets the four young men. She believes them to be Sethu's friends after seeing his photo at their house. The four cook up a story about an affair Sethu had with a girl.\n\nHearing the news that the four men are friends of Sethu, the burglar, John Honai, kidnaps them in order to retrieve a mysterious briefcase. Maya, in search of her brother's lover,finds details of Annie Philip ([[Rekha (South Indian actress)|Rekha]]), who was a friend of her brother's from the library. Annie is now a nun in a church and adopted the name Sister Josephine. Josephine narrates about her history with Sethu when questioned by Maya. Andrew's father was a businessman who was murdered by John Honai's father and he built a business empire with the money taken from Andrew's father. Andrews creates trouble in that business to take revenge. Honai's father then sells all his assets and tries to run away with the money in the briefcase, but gets murdered by Andrews on the way.Later,Andrews is seen murdered on a [[beach]]. \n\nSethu arrives at Harihar Nagar to give this money to Ammachi, but when he finds out that Ammachi is ignorant of Andrews's death and is still waiting for him, he gives it to Annie, who was Andrews's girlfriend. After returning to Bombay, Sethu gives John Honai a briefcase similar to the one given to Annie, but when Honai opens it, he finds it full of bricks and stones. Angered,he murders Sethu.\n\nThe four young men who were kidnapped by Honai manage to escape and are chased by Honai and his associates. Soon, Maya and her grandparents are also kidnapped by Honai but the four young men rescue them. Ammachi comes to know about Andrew's death from Sister Josephine, who gives her the briefcase. While Ammachi is cooking dinner, Honai comes to her house to get the briefcase. Ammachi removes the fuse lights are switched off. After trying to find Ammachi, Honai unknowingly lights a lighter near the gas stove which was switched on, and is burned to death.\n\nIn the end, Maya and her grandparents are shown moving out. Maya gives the four young men the briefcase, which they open and see that it is full of treasure.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]] as Mahadevan\n* [[Siddique (actor)|Siddique]] as Govindan Kutty\n* [[Jagadish]] as Appukuttan\n* [[Ashokan (actor)|Ashokan]] as Thomas Kutty\n* [[Suresh Gopi]] as Sethumadhavan\n* [[Saikumar (Malayalam actor)|Saikumar]] as Andrews\n* [[Riza Bava]] as John Honai\n* [[Geetha Vijayan]] as Maya\n* [[Rekha (Tamil actress)|Rekha]] as Sister Josephine / Annie Phillip\n* [[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]] as Andrews's mother\n* [[Philomina]] as Sethumadhavan's and Maya's grandmother\n* [[Paravoor Bharathan]] as Sethumadhavan's and Maya's grandfather\n* [[Appa Haja]] as Cherian\n* [[Thrissur Elsy]] as Mahadevan's mother\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe soundtrack features two super hit songs composed by [[S. Balakrishnan (composer)|S. Balakrishnan]] and lyrics penned by [[Bichu Thirumala]]. The songs were remixed and used by [[Alex Paul]] for [[2 Harihar Nagar]], the first sequel of this film.\n# \"Ekantha Chandrike\" - [[M. G. Sreekumar]], [[Unni Menon]]\n# \"Unnam Marannu\"     - [[M. G. Sreekumar]], [[Choir|Chorus]]\n\n==Sequels==\n19 years after the release of the original, ''In Harihar Nagar'' had a sequel ''[[2 Harihar Nagar]]'' directed by Lal of the director-duo [[Siddique-Lal]]. It was released on 1 April 2009. After its success, Lal planned another sequel, named ''[[In Ghost House Inn]]''. It was released on 25 March 2010.\n\n==Remake versions==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\" class=sortable\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"|-\n\n! Year\n! Film\n! Language\n! Cast\n! Director\n! Ref\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[MGR Nagaril (1991 film)|MGR Nagaril]]''\n|[[Tamil cinema|Tamil]]\n|[[Anand Babu]], [[Sukanya]], [[Vivek (actor)|Vivek]], [[Charle]], [[Shankar (actor)|Shankar]], [[Napoleon (actor)|Napoleon]]\n| Alleppy Ashraf\n|<ref>{{cite book|last= National Film Development Corporation of India |first= |title= Cinema in India: Volume 2 |edition= |series=Cinema in India |year= 1991|publisher= |location= India|language=|isbn= 0-333-93410-5|page=85|chapter=}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''Madhuranagarilo''\n|[[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n|[[Meka Srikanth|Srikanth]], Nirosha\n|[[Kodi Ramakrishna]]\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Nagaradalli Nayakaru]]''\n|Kannada\n|[[Malashri]], [[Chi. Guru Dutt]], Sunil, Balaraj, [[Betha Sudhakar|Sudhakar]]\n|Om Sai Prakash\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Parda Hai Parda (1992 film)|Parda Hai Parda]]''\n|[[Hindi cinema|Hindi]]\n|[[Chunky Pandey]], [[Meena Durairaj|Meena]], [[Laxmikant Berde]], [[Kiran Kumar]]\n|[[K. Bapaiah]]\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Dhol (2007 film)|Dhol]]''\n|[[Hindi cinema|Hindi]]\n|[[Sharman Joshi]], [[Kunal Khemu]], [[Rajpal Yadav]], [[Tusshar Kapoor]], [[Tanushree Dutta]], [[Arbaaz Khan]]\n|[[Priyadarshan]]\n|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2007/09/22/stories/2007092250530200.htm|title=Fun and frolic |author=Sreedhar Pillai|newspaper=The Hindu|date=22 September 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n* Another Tamil version of the film, titled ''Idhu MGR Illam'', was under production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinesouth.com/masala/hotnews/new/24022006-3.shtml|title=Raj Kiran's 'Idhu MGR Illam'|publisher=Cinesouth.com|date=24 February 2006}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0278501}}\n\n{{Siddique (director)}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s Malayalam-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian comedy thriller films]]\n[[Category:1990s comedy thriller films]]\n[[Category:Malayalam films remade in other languages]]\n[[Category:Malayalam films in series|In1]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2010}} \n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = In Harihar Nagar\n| image          = In Harihar Nagar.jpg\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Siddique-Lal]]\n| producer       = Khais-Kuriachan\n| writer         = Siddique-Lal\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]]<br>[[Siddique (actor)|Siddique]]<br>[[Jagadish]]<br>[[Ashokan (actor)|Ashokan]]\n| music          = [[S. Balakrishnan (composer)|S. Balakrishnan]]\n| cinematography = [[Venu (cinematographer)|Venu]]\n| editing        = Gaurishekar K. R.\n| distributor    = Swargachitra\n| studio         = Mohsin Priya Combines\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1990}}\n| runtime        =\n| country        = India\n| language       = [[Malayalam]]\n}}\n\n'''''In Harihar Nagar''''' is a 1990 Indian [[Malayalam]]-language [[Comedy film|comedy]] [[Thriller film|thriller]] film written and directed by [[Siddique-Lal]]. It stars [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]], [[Siddique (actor)|Siddique]], [[Jagadish]] and [[Ashokan (actor)|Ashokan]] as four happy-go-lucky best friends competing to woo their new neighbor girl. The film's music was composed by [[S. Balakrishnan (composer)|S. Balakrishnan]].\n\nThe film was a commercial success at the box office. It has been recognised as one of the iconic comedy films in Malayalam cinema.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2009/01/02/stories/2009010250630200.htm|title=Return to Harihar Nagar |author=Vijay George|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=2 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/malayalam/top-stories/2008/in-harihar-nagar-2-090908.html|title=In Harihar Nagar-2|date=9 September 2008|publisher=[[Oneindia.in]]|accessdate=2 January 2011}}</ref> The film has spawned two sequels\u2014''[[2 Harihar Nagar]]'' (2009) and ''[[In Ghost House Inn]]'' (2010), both directed by [[Lal (director)|Lal]]. ''In Harihar Nagar'' was remade twice in [[Hindi]] as ''[[Parda Hai Parda (1992 film)|Parda Hai Parda]]'' and ''[[Dhol (film)|Dhol]]'', in [[Kannada]] as ''[[Nagaradalli Nayakaru]]'', in [[Tamil language|Tamil]] as ''[[MGR Nagaril (1991 film)|MGR Nagaril]]'', and in [[Telugu language|Telugu]] as ''Madhuranagarilo''.\n\n==Plot==\n{{copyedit |date=April 2020}}\nMahadevan ([[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]]), Govindan Kutty ([[Siddique (actor)|Siddique]]), Appukuttan ([[Jagadish]]) and Thomas Kutty ([[Ashokan (actor)|Ashokan]]) are four young men who live in the housing colony named 'Harihar Nagar.' The movie starts with an incident that takes place in [[Mumbai|Bombay]], where a burglar, John Honai, breaks in looking for a specific briefcase. In the next scene the four young men make an appearance, using their wiles to impress young, neighborhood girls. A girl, Maya ([[Geetha Vijayan]]), along with her grandparents relocate to Harihar Nagar and happen to be Mahadevan's new neighbors. The four try to win her over on many occasions. One day they see her posting a letter and they bribe the postman to get hold of the letter. On reading the contents of the letter, they learn that Maya has come to Harihar Nagar to learn about the death of her brother - Sethu Madhavan ([[Suresh Gopi]]). \n\nMaya visits the house of Andrew's ([[Saikumar (Malayalam actor)|Saikumar]]), a friend of Sethu Madhavan. She asks Andrew's mother, called Ammachi by him and his friends, ([[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]]) to contact her if she gets any information about her brother. The four men approach Ammachi, pretending to be Sethu's friends. They manage to get Sethu's photograph by telling her that they want it for the colony's sports club. Maya gets this information from Ammachi and meets the four young men. She believes them to be Sethu's friends after seeing his photo at their house. The four cook up a story about an affair Sethu had with a girl.\n\nHearing the news that the four men are friends of Sethu, the burglar, John Honai, kidnaps them in order to retrieve a mysterious briefcase. Maya, in search of her brother's lover,finds details of Annie Philip ([[Rekha (South Indian actress)|Rekha]]), who was a friend of her brother's from the library. Annie is now a nun in a church and adopted the name Sister Josephine. Josephine narrates about her history with Sethu when questioned by Maya. Andrew's father was a businessman who was murdered by John Honai's father and he built a business empire with the money taken from Andrew's father. Andrews creates trouble in that business to take revenge. Honai's father then sells all his assets and tries to run away with the money in the briefcase, but gets murdered by Andrews on the way.Later,Andrews is seen murdered on a [[beach]]. \n\nSethu arrives at Harihar Nagar to give this money to Ammachi, but when he finds out that Ammachi is ignorant of Andrews's death and is still waiting for him, he gives it to Annie, who was Andrews's girlfriend. After returning to Bombay, Sethu gives John Honai a briefcase similar to the one given to Annie, but when Honai opens it, he finds it full of bricks and stones. Angered,he murders Sethu.\n\nThe four young men who were kidnapped by Honai manage to escape and are chased by Honai and his associates. Soon, Maya and her grandparents are also kidnapped by Honai but the four young men rescue them. Ammachi comes to know about Andrew's death from Sister Josephine, who gives her the briefcase. While Ammachi is cooking dinner, Honai comes to her house to get the briefcase. Ammachi removes the fuse lights are switched off. After trying to find Ammachi, Honai unknowingly lights a lighter near the gas stove which was switched on, and is burned to death.\n\nIn the end, Maya and her grandparents are shown moving out. Maya gives the four young men the briefcase, which they open and see that it is full of treasure.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Mukesh (actor)|Mukesh]] as Mahadevan\n* [[Siddique (actor)|Siddique]] as Govindan Kutty\n* [[Jagadish]] as Appukuttan\n* [[Ashokan (actor)|Ashokan]] as Thomas Kutty\n* [[Suresh Gopi]] as Sethumadhavan\n* [[Saikumar (Malayalam actor)|Saikumar]] as Andrews\n* [[Riza Bava]] as John Honai\n* [[Geetha Vijayan]] as Maya\n* [[Rekha (Tamil actress)|Rekha]] as Sister Josephine / Annie Phillip\n* [[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]] as Andrews's mother\n* [[Philomina]] as Sethumadhavan's and Maya's grandmother\n* [[Paravoor Bharathan]] as Sethumadhavan's and Maya's grandfather\n* [[Appa Haja]] as Cherian\n* [[Thrissur Elsy]] as Mahadevan's mother\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe soundtrack features two super hit songs composed by [[S. Balakrishnan (composer)|S. Balakrishnan]] and lyrics penned by [[Bichu Thirumala]]. The songs were remixed and used by [[Alex Paul]] for [[2 Harihar Nagar]], the first sequel of this film.\n# \"Ekantha Chandrike\" - [[M. G. Sreekumar]], [[Unni Menon]]\n# \"Unnam Marannu\"     - [[M. G. Sreekumar]], [[Choir|Chorus]]\n\n==Sequels==\n19 years after the release of the original, ''In Harihar Nagar'' had a sequel ''[[2 Harihar Nagar]]'' directed by Lal of the director-duo [[Siddique-Lal]]. It was released on 1 April 2009. After its success, Lal planned another sequel, named ''[[In Ghost House Inn]]''. It was released on 25 March 2010.\n\n==Remake versions==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\" class=sortable\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"|-\n\n! Year\n! Film\n! Language\n! Cast\n! Director\n! Ref\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[MGR Nagaril (1991 film)|MGR Nagaril]]''\n|[[Tamil cinema|Tamil]]\n|[[Anand Babu]], [[Sukanya]], [[Vivek (actor)|Vivek]], [[Charle]], [[Shankar (actor)|Shankar]], [[Napoleon (actor)|Napoleon]]\n| Alleppy Ashraf\n|<ref>{{cite book|last= National Film Development Corporation of India |first= |title= Cinema in India: Volume 2 |edition= |series=Cinema in India |year= 1991|publisher= |location= India|language=|isbn= 0-333-93410-5|page=85|chapter=}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''Madhuranagarilo''\n|[[Telugu language|Telugu]]\n|[[Meka Srikanth|Srikanth]], Nirosha\n|[[Kodi Ramakrishna]]\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Nagaradalli Nayakaru]]''\n|Kannada\n|[[Malashri]], [[Chi. Guru Dutt]], Sunil, Balaraj, [[Betha Sudhakar|Sudhakar]]\n|Om Sai Prakash\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Parda Hai Parda (1992 film)|Parda Hai Parda]]''\n|[[Hindi cinema|Hindi]]\n|[[Chunky Pandey]], [[Meena Durairaj|Meena]], [[Laxmikant Berde]], [[Kiran Kumar]]\n|[[K. Bapaiah]]\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Dhol (2007 film)|Dhol]]''\n|[[Hindi cinema|Hindi]]\n|[[Sharman Joshi]], [[Kunal Khemu]], [[Rajpal Yadav]], [[Tusshar Kapoor]], [[Tanushree Dutta]], [[Arbaaz Khan]]\n|[[Priyadarshan]]\n|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2007/09/22/stories/2007092250530200.htm|title=Fun and frolic |author=Sreedhar Pillai|newspaper=The Hindu|date=22 September 2007}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n* Another Tamil version of the film, titled ''Idhu MGR Illam'', was under production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinesouth.com/masala/hotnews/new/24022006-3.shtml|title=Raj Kiran's 'Idhu MGR Illam'|publisher=Cinesouth.com|date=24 February 2006}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0278501}}\n\n{{Siddique (director)}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s Malayalam-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian comedy thriller films]]\n[[Category:1990s comedy thriller films]]\n[[Category:Malayalam films remade in other languages]]\n[[Category:Malayalam films in series|In1]]\n", "name_user": "Rakshit Mathur", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In_Harihar_Nagar"}
